@@ -0,0 +1,15 @@
+BusinessFlow to AFF session seam is intact for the tested unauthenticated `GET /FireFlow/api/session` path.
+
+Evidence:
+- Apache config in `artifacts/aff.conf.snapshot` maps `/FireFlow/api` to `http://localhost:1989/aff/api/external`, so `https://localhost/FireFlow/api/session` should land on `http://localhost:1989/aff/api/external/session`.
+- `artifacts/apache-session.body` and `artifacts/direct-session.body` returned the same JSON payload: `{"valid":false,"message":{"code":"INVALID_SESSION_KEY","message":"The session key provided is invalid"}}`.
+- Apache added only edge headers on the 443 path. The backend response semantics matched the direct `aff-boot` path.
+- Listener ownership is consistent with that seam: Apache is bound on `:443`, and `ss -ltnp '( sport = :1989 )'` showed port `1989` owned by Java PID `1687`. `artifacts/aff-boot.service.show.txt` shows `aff-boot.service` active and running as user `afa`.
+
+Close backend clue for the next seam:
+- `artifacts/aff-boot-session-window.log` shows `GET /aff/api/external/session` requests succeeding with HTTP 200 on the `1989` backend during the same window.
+- `fireflow.log` showed nearby `UserSessionPersistenceEventHandler` and `FABridge` session activity, including session extension and metro calls. If parity ever breaks, stop next at AFF session handling around those log lines before moving further upstream.
+
+Notes:
+- `ssl_error_log` did not show an AFF-specific proxy failure in the sampled tail. The visible proxy noise was unrelated `autodiscovery` DNS lookup failures.
+- This was observe-only. No target files were intentionally modified.

